  <section class="row">
    <h4>Description</h4>
    <p>Students will change the fractional amounts in a recipe into multiples of the unit fraction,
    <abbr title="one fourth">¼</abbr>, in order to accurately mix ingredients using only a <abbr title="one fourth">¼</abbr> measuring cup. They will be composing equivalent fractions using unit fractions and representing them in a variety of ways. As an option, the recipe can be prepared and baked by the class.</p>
    
    <h4>Mathematics</h4>
    <p>Decomposing fractions is important in order for students to gain a concrete understanding of the relationship between a pair of equivalent fractions. Using concrete and visual representations like drawings or measuring cups are beneficial when proving equivalency.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="row">
    <h4>Curriculum Connections</h4>
    <p>Students will:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>decompose fractions into unit fractions</li>
      <li>count by unit fractions</li>
      <li>compare fractions with friendly but unlike denominators</li>
      <li>generate equivalent fractions using models</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="row">
    <h4>Instructional sequence</h4>
    <ol>
      <li>Partner the students.</li>
      <li>Introduce task: You want to bake some cookies but you only have a <abbr title="one fourth">¼</abbr> measuring cup. Refer to the <abbr title="Blackline Master">BLM</abbr>.</li>
      <li>After the students have worked on a solution, (e.g., Students could record using: concrete objects, drawing – area or set models) consolidate their learning by having a few students share their work.</li>
      <li>Consolidate the learning using the key questions.</li>
      <li>Get the students to independently place all of the recipe fractions on a number line. Have the students also write the equivalent fractions in fourths. (1 <abbr title="one half"><sup>1</sup>/<sub>2</sub></abbr> = <abbr title="one fourth"><sup>1</sup>/<sub>4</sub></abbr> + <abbr title="one fourth"><sup>1</sup>/<sub>4</sub></abbr> + <abbr title="one fourth"><sup>1</sup>/<sub>4</sub></abbr> + <abbr title="one fourth"><sup>1</sup>/<sub>4</sub></abbr> + <abbr title="one fourth"><sup>1</sup>/<sub>4</sub></abbr> + <abbr title="one fourth"><sup>1</sup>/<sub>4</sub></abbr> = <abbr title="six fourths"><sup>6</sup>/<sub>4</sub></abbr> ).</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-6 col-md-6 no-padding-left">
      <h4>Highlights of student thinking</h4>
      <p>Students may:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>make connections to money (0.25 = <abbr title="one fourth"><sup>1</sup>/<sub>4</sub></abbr>)</li>
        <li>use a variety of concrete models: area, set, volume</li>
        <li>write the fractions on the number line in many ways 1 <abbr title="one half"><sup>1</sup>/<sub>2</sub></abbr>, 1 <abbr title="two fourths"><sup>2</sup>/<sub>4</sub></abbr>, <abbr title="six fourths"><sup>6</sup>/<sub>4</sub></abbr> </li>
        <li>This could be addressed in the consolidation</li>
        <li>use mixed and improper fractions interchangeably</li>
        <li>struggle with:
          <ul>
            <li>partitioning their number line into unit fractions</li>
            <li>transferring knowledge to number line.  </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-6">
      <h4>Key questions</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>What model did you use to decompose or break down the given fractions?</li>
        <li>How did your unit fraction ( <abbr title="one fourth"><sup>1</sup>/<sub>4</sub></abbr> ) compare to the fractional amounts in the recipe?</li>
        <li>How did you recognize the equivalent fractions on the number line?</li>
        <li>Can you write your mixed fraction as an improper fraction?</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

